# kernel best practices

## always clean up browsers

delete browsers when done. wrap everything in `try/finally`. set `timeout_seconds` as a safety net.

```typescript
const browser = await kernel.browsers.create({ timeout_seconds: 300 });
try {
  // work
} finally {
  await kernel.browsers.deleteByID(browser.session_id);
}
```

## use stealth mode for real websites

stealth mode automatically adds a recaptcha solver and residential proxy. use `stealth: true` whenever you're hitting a real website — most production sites have bot detection.

## set timeouts

always set `timeout_seconds`. sessions can run up to 72 hours max. use the shortest timeout that lets your task complete. kernel doesn't charge for idle time, but don't leave browsers running forever.

## use profiles for auth

don't hardcode credentials. use browser profiles to persist login sessions. kernel manages auth so agents can log in and stay logged in across the internet.

## pick the right tool

- `execute_playwright_code`: quick, self-contained tasks. no local playwright needed.
- sdk + CDP connection: complex multi-step automations, local file access, long sessions.

## handle errors

browser automation fails. network errors, selector mismatches, timeouts — expect them. always ensure browser cleanup runs in a `finally` block regardless of what goes wrong.

## proxy quality matters

for sites with IP-based blocking: mobile > residential > ISP > datacenter. stealth mode includes a residential proxy by default. add a dedicated proxy only for geo-targeting or when the default isn't enough.

## don't hoard browsers

create browsers when you need them, use them, delete them. don't spin up browsers in advance "just in case."
